{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496392"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:45:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:45:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1350"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1350"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.09,0.06,0.59,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1350"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110374"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1350"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1350"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92647"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"714"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2023"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2201"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14743"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41656"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42291"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110374"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a three-month history of worsening chest pain on exertion. The pain is located in the middle of her chest, radiating to her left arm. She also describes worsening calf pain on exertion, occurring over a similar timeline. She has no medical history other than worsening vision over the last five years requiring glasses. She has no regular medications and does not smoke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she has the following skin lesion (Image) located on her right antecubital fossa. On further questioning, she says that it has been present since her early 20s and has not changed since then. Angioid streaks were found on fundoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ehlers-Danlos syndrome","Segmental vitiligo","Cutis laxa","Pseudoxanthoma elasticum","Marfan syndrome"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an example of \u003Cstrong\u003Epseudoxanthoma elasticum, \u003C/strong\u003Ea genetic disorder that leads to degeneration of elastic tissue and premature atherosclerosis. The changes often manifest in the skin first, where yellow, thickened areas occur. This often starts on the lateral neck first before progressing to flexural folds of limbs (\u0027plucked chicken skin\u0027 appearance). The changes to blood vessels can lead to early atherosclerotic changes (angina, claudication), cardiomyopathy, chronic gastrointestinal blood loss and retinal haemorrhage (characterised by progressive visual loss and angioid streaks on fundoscopy).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEhlers-Danlos syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a group of inherited disorders that involve a genetic defect in collagen or connective tissue synthesis and structure. This results in varying degrees of hyper-extensive skin and joint hypermobility, and tissue and vascular fragility. Retinal involvement can include angioid streaks as well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESegmental vitiligo\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a single white patch, often affecting young people. It is characterised by a well-defined milky-white patch of the skin. It would not have the affect on premature atherosclerosis or angioid streaks on fundoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECutis laxa\u003C/strong\u003E is a connective tissue disorder characterised by loosely hanging skin that lacks elasticity. Predominately the loose skin appearance is around the eyes, face, neck, shoulders, and thighs which is not present in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMarfan syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a connective tissue disorder typically associated with cardiovascular features (mitral valve prolapse, aortic aneurysm, and dissection), musculoskeletal features (tall stature with disproportionally long extremities, and joint hypermobility), and the eyes (subluxation of the lens, angioid streaks on fundoscopy). Skin findings in Marfan syndrome are typically striae rather than white areas as shown here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pseudoxanthoma elasticum can be associated with an increased risk of early atherosclerotic changes."],"references":["DermNet NZ. Pseudoxanthoma elasticum. DermNet [online]. 2021. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/pseudoxanthoma-elasticum/","DermNet NZ. Vitiligo. DermNet [online]. 2021. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/vitiligo/","DermNet NZ. Cutis laxa. DermNet [online]. 2021. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/cutis-laxa/","DermNet NZ. Ehlers\u2013Danlos syndrome. DermNet [online]. 2021. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/ehlers-danlos-syndrome/","DermNet NZ. Marfan syndrome. DermNet [online]. 2021. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/marfan-syndrome/","Marconi B, Bobyr I, Campanati A, Molinelli E, Consales V, Brisigotti V, Scarpelli M, Racchini S, Offidani A. Pseudoxanthoma elasticum and skin: Clinical manifestations, histopathology, pathomechanism, perspectives of treatment. Intractable Rare Dis Res. 2015 Aug;4(3):113-22. doi: 10.5582/irdr.2015.01014. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4561240/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92647"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1350"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18478"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18478"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2ef0f516-fc34-4e49-8b8e-7e2229f6ee00.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2ef0f516-fc34-4e49-8b8e-7e2229f6ee00.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92647"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-30T16:06:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-30T16:06:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1350"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110374"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"